# maritime-flow

## Project Overview
Maritime vessel tracking and intelligence system for the Eastern
Mediterranean. Receives AIS data from a self-operated field receiver
on Troodos, Cyprus. Detects anomalous vessel behaviour and infers
trade flows. Built as a companion learning project to air-cargo,
specifically for Apache Spark, SedonaSQL, and Delta Lake.

## Repository Structure
maritime-flow/
├── ais-collector-nmea/     Go app — UDP NMEA listener on Pi 4
│                           receives from field phone, → Redpanda
├── ais-collector-websocket/ Java — WebSocket client (dormant)
│                           was aisstream.io collector
│                           kept in case a stream source returns
├── ais-analyser/           Spark + SedonaSQL batch analytical engine
│                           reads accumulated NMEA from Pi 4 Redpanda
│                           writes to Delta Lake
├── common/                 Shared models, NMEA parsing, MMSI handling
├── reference-data/         PostGIS DDL scripts, OurAIS reference data
│                           airspace/coverage polygon scripts
└── k8s/                    K3s manifests — Spark Operator on Minisforum

## Language and Build
- ais-collector-nmea: Go 1.22+
- All other modules: Java 17, Maven, no parent pom
- Do not suggest Gradle, Kotlin, or Spring Boot
- Do not fetch external URLs autonomously
- If documentation needed, ask user to provide the section

## Core Technology Stack
- Apache Spark — batch analytical engine (not Flink — see design decisions)
- Apache SedonaSQL — spatial operations in SparkSQL
- Redpanda — Kafka-compatible broker (always-on on Pi 4)
- PostgreSQL + PostGIS — spatial reference layers, operational state
- Delta Lake — analytical archive (Spark's native format)
- DuckDB — ad-hoc queries on Delta Lake tables
- Go — ais-collector-nmea (single binary, no JVM, systemd service)
- Jackson — JSON serialisation in Java modules
- MQTT (Mosquitto) — field node command/control and telemetry

## Why Spark not Flink
maritime-flow is a batch analytical system, not a real-time streaming
system. Data accumulates on Pi 4 Redpanda while Minisforum is off.
Spark batch processes the accumulated data on demand. This is the
opposite of air-cargo which uses Flink for stateful per-aircraft
streaming. The two projects are deliberately complementary:

  air-cargo:       Flink streaming → Iceberg
  maritime-flow:   Spark batch → Delta Lake

Flink → Iceberg and Spark → Delta Lake are both structurally correct
pairings. Do not suggest switching maritime-flow to Flink.

## Infrastructure
Field node (Troodos/Czubek, Cyprus):
  BraX2 phone + RTL-SDR V4 via USB OTG
  AIS-catcher for Android — decodes AIS, forwards NMEA
  Mobile data SIM (CYTA) — forwards to AISHub + Pi 4
  LiFePO4 power bank + flexible solar panel
  MQTT: subscribes to commands, publishes health/photos

Pi 4 at home (always on):
  Receives NMEA from field phone via UDP (port 10110)
  ais-collector-nmea (Go, systemd) → Redpanda ais.nmea
  Mosquitto MQTT broker — field node command/control
  DuckDNS — keeps home IP mapped to hostname
  Wireguard VPN — remote access from anywhere
  USB SSD (2TB) — long-term raw NMEA archive

Minisforum CachyOS (run on demand):
  K3s: Spark Operator, PostGIS StatefulSet
  Spark reads from Pi 4 Redpanda
  Processes accumulated NMEA in batch
  Writes analytical results to Delta Lake

No Hetzner — was planned for aisstream.io WebSocket relay.
aisstream.io went dark March 2026. Architecture does not need
always-on cloud relay. Pi 4 is the always-on component.

## Kafka Topics (on Pi 4 Redpanda)
  ais.nmea          raw NMEA sentences from field phone
                    key = MMSI, value = NMEA string
                    long retention — this is the raw archive
                    all downstream processing reads from here

No topic proliferation. One raw topic, Spark reads and processes.
Do not create intermediate Kafka topics.

## MQTT Topics
  field/troodos/commands      Pi → phone
                              "snap-panel", "snap-sea",
                              "reboot", "status", "restart-ais"
  field/troodos/photos        phone → Pi (base64 image)
  field/troodos/health        phone → Pi (battery, signal, uptime)
  field/troodos/nmea          phone → Pi (NMEA via MQTT, QoS 1)
  agro/+/+                    future agricultural sensors

## Delta Lake Tables (on Minisforum)
  vessels           enriched per-vessel state, one row per MMSI
                    MERGE on update — Delta Lake MERGE semantics
  tracks            vessel position history, OBSERVED tier only
                    partitioned by date + mmsi
                    Z-ordered by (latitude, longitude)
  gaps              gap records — Tier 1 facts only
                    gap_classification populated by batch job
  implied_tracks    tessellated great circle display geometries
                    display_only=true, never joined analytically

## Track Point Tiers
Three tiers — must never be mixed in analytical data:
  Tier 1: OBSERVED      real AIS positions, full analytical value
  Tier 2: INFERRED      analytically deduced, carry uncertainty score
  Tier 3: TESSELLATION  geometric rendering nodes, no analytical value
                        stored only in implied_tracks display table

## Serialisation
- ais.nmea: raw NMEA strings — never transcode external data
- Delta Lake: Parquet columnar, lat/lon as double columns
- PostgreSQL: JSONB for operational state
- Internal: Protobuf for any future event topics

## ais-collector-nmea (Go)
Plain Go console app, systemd service on Pi 4.
Single binary, no JVM, ~10-15MB memory.

Structure:
  main.go              UDP socket loop, DatagramSocket on port 10110
  nmea_validator.go    checksum + format check
  mmsi_extractor.go    pulls MMSI from sentence for Kafka key
  kafka_producer.go    standard Kafka client → Redpanda
  config.go            UDP port + bootstrap servers from env vars

Kafka topic: ais.nmea, key=MMSI, value=raw NMEA string
systemd service: Restart=always, env vars for config

## ais-collector-websocket (Java, DORMANT)
Original aisstream.io WebSocket client.
aisstream.io went dark March 2026.
Keep code intact — do not delete or modify.
A future WebSocket AIS feed may emerge.
README explains the history and dormant status.

## ais-analyser (Spark + SedonaSQL)
Batch processing of accumulated NMEA from Pi 4 Redpanda.
Runs on demand on Minisforum via K3s Spark Operator.

Spark + Sedona Docker image:
  BASE: apache/spark:3.4.1
  DO NOT use apache/sedona image — it bundles its own Spark
  master/worker, clashes with Spark Operator.
  Layer Sedona on top of apache/spark base image.

SparkSQL + SedonaSQL for spatial queries.
Delta Lake for analytical output.
MERGE semantics for vessel record updates.
OPTIMIZE ZORDER BY (latitude, longitude) for spatial queries.

## PostGIS Reference Layers (reference schema)
  reference.ports              port polygons
  reference.anchorages         anchorage polygons
  reference.coastline          land/sea boundary
  reference.coverage_zones     ADS-B/AIS coverage classification
                               hand-drawn in QGIS
                               NORMAL | COVERAGE_HOLE | OCEAN
  reference.airspace_restrictions  overflight bans, conflict zones
                               DATA_SUPPRESSION zones (China etc.)

## Coverage Gap Classification
Not all gaps are equal:
  OCEAN:              landing impossible, flight/voyage continued
  COVERAGE_HOLE:      land area, no receivers, ambiguous
  REGULATORY_SUPPRESSION: data actively prevented from leaving
                          country (China, North Korea etc.)
                          treat as data void
  ANOMALOUS:          gap in well-covered area — high signal

## AIS Technical Notes
VHF 162MHz, two channels, TDMA self-organising.
Class A (large commercial): transmits every 2-10 seconds
Class B (smaller vessels): every 30 seconds
NMEA 0183 format — sentences starting with ! or $
AIS is open unencrypted radio — legally receivable by anyone.
aisstream.io went dark — do not depend on any third-party feed.
Own receiver is the primary data source.

## Key Identifiers
MMSI:       Maritime Mobile Service Identity — primary vessel key
            9 digits, always string (leading zeros significant)
IMO:        International Maritime Organization number
            permanent vessel identifier, more stable than MMSI
            but not always present in AIS messages
Callsign:   changes, not reliable as identifier

## Vessel Types of Interest
Tankers (crude, product, chemical, LNG)
Bulk carriers
Container ships
Cargo vessels
Military/government vessels
Fishing vessels (IUU detection)

## Spatial Operations
- ST_DistanceSphere for distance calculations
- ST_Within for port/anchorage proximity
- ST_DWithin with geography cast for metre-accurate proximity
- Coordinates always WGS84 (EPSG:4326)
- AIS data: longitude first, latitude second in position reports
  be explicit when constructing geometry points
- Position on land = spoofing signal — do NOT filter it out

## Anomaly Scoring
Fuzzy 0.0-1.0 scores throughout. No binary thresholds.
Scores accumulate in per-vessel Spark state.

Signals:
  Dark period in covered area          high score
  AIS position on land                 hard anomaly (spoofing)
  Speed physically impossible          hard anomaly
  STS (ship-to-ship) transfer          medium score
  Port call in sanctioned location     high score
  Route deviation from baseline        medium score
  Gap classification: ANOMALOUS        high score
  Gap classification: COVERAGE_HOLE    low/zero score

## Design Decisions
- Spark not Flink — batch analytical workload, not streaming
- Delta Lake not Iceberg — Spark's native format, first-class support
- Pi 4 always on, Minisforum on demand — raw-first data accumulation
- No Hetzner — aisstream.io dead, own receiver eliminates need
- No aisstream.io dependency — self-operated field node
- Raw NMEA preserved in Redpanda — never transcode external data
- Go for ais-collector-nmea — single binary, no JVM on Pi 4
- One raw Kafka topic — no intermediate topic proliferation
- DuckDB for ad-hoc Delta Lake queries — no query engine needed
- Coverage polygons in PostGIS — editable in QGIS, JDBC joins
- UN sanctions only — unilateral sanctions not treated as law
- Observational language — never judgemental terminology
  (anomalous behaviour, not violation)
- Position on land is anomaly signal, not filter candidate
- Track point tiers strictly separated — tessellation never
  stored in analytical tables

## What This Project Is NOT
- Not a real-time system — batch processing on demand
- Not dependent on any paid or third-party data source
- Not attempting global coverage — Eastern Med focus
- Not a sanctions enforcement tool
- Not always-on — Pi 4 is always on, Minisforum is not

